d","County Meath, Ireland":"County Meath, Ierland","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ierland"},"en":{"–1244":"–1244","1171–1244":"1171–1244","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1208–Male":"1208–Deceased","1210–Male":"1210–Deceased","1212–Female":"1212–Deceased","–Male":"Deceased","1206":"1206","about 1206":"about 1206","1212":"1212","abt 1208":"about 1208","1244":"1244","1210":"1210","abt 1210":"about 1210","1171":"1171","1208":"1208","abt 1212":"about 1212","Castle Carrickfergus, Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ulster Province, Ireland":"Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ireland","of Drumrany, W-Meath., Irln.":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland","of Drumrany, W-Mth, Irln":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland","County Meath, Ireland":"County Meath, Ireland","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland","nameMeanings":[{"name":"DeCourcy","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English and Irish (of Norman origin): variant of   Decoursey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Decoursey","meanings":["English and Irish: of Norman origin, a variant of <b>De Courcy</b>, a habitational name for someone from any of various places in northern France called Courcy, especially the one in Calvados. <i>Courcy</i> is from the Gallo-Roman personal name <i>Curtius</i> (a derivative of Latin <i>curtus</i> ‘short’; compare   Court   3) + the locative suffix <i>-acum</i>.","History: Patrick de Courcy was appointed justiciar of Ireland in 1221."]}]},{"name":"Maud","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Maud DeCourcy was born as the daughter of John DeCourcy. She had at least 3 sons and 1 daughter with Henry De Leon. She died in 1244."},"et":{"–1244":"–1244","1171–1244":"1171–1244","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1208–Male":"1208–Surnud","1210–Male":"1210–Surnud","1212–Female":"1212–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1206":"1206","about 1206":"umbes 1206","1212":"1212","abt 1208":"umbes 1208","1244":"1244","1210":"1210","abt 1210":"umbes 1210","1171":"1171","1208":"1208","abt 1212":"umbes 1212","Castle Carrickfergus, Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ulster Province, Ireland":"Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Iirimaa","of Drumrany, W-Meath., Irln.":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Iirimaa","of Drumrany, W-Mth, Irln":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Iirimaa","County Meath, Ireland":"County Meath, Iirimaa","Drumraney, County Westmeath, Ireland":"Drumraney, County Westmeath, Iirimaa"},"fi":{"–1244":"–1244","1171–1244":"1171–1244","1206–1244":"1206–1244","1208–Male":"1208–Kuollut","1210–Male":"1210–Kuollut","1212–Female":"1212–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1206":"1206","about 1206":"noin 1206","1212":"1212","abt 1208":"noin 1208","1244":"1244","1210":"1210","abt 1210":"noin 1210","1171":"1171","1208":"1208","abt 1212":"noin 1212","Castle Carrickfergus, Carrickfergus, County Antrim, Ulster Provin